#week-title("Two", "Westcott, Canseliet & the Final Inner Requirement")

=== Core Teaching

Two texts return in Month 10 that were first introduced in Year Three Month 1:
Westcott's *Science of Alchemy* and Canseliet's *Two Alchemical Abodes*. Read
at the beginning of the mineral work, they provided an orientation. Read again
now, from the accumulated experience of Year Three, they reveal dimensions that
were inaccessible at the start.

*Westcott's Cosmic Level revisited.* At Month 1, the Cosmic level of the
triple point was the most abstract — the practitioner had not yet experienced
what "operating in accordance with universal laws" feels like from inside the
mineral work. By Month 10, the practitioner who has been conducting Via Humida
cycles, observing sealed preparations weekly, and maintaining the long
circulation has had repeated experience of something that is difficult to name
but unmistakeable when present: the sense that the Work is proceeding by its
own inner logic, that the practitioner's role is to tend and observe rather
than to produce and force.

This is the Cosmic level in experience: not a philosophical abstraction but
a directly perceptible quality of how the Work unfolds when approached rightly.
Westcott calls it the reconciliation of the Protyle — the universal undifferentiated
first matter — with modern scientific understanding. At the experiential level,
it is the recognition that the Stone's projection is not a miracle but the
natural consequence of the Work having been done correctly.

*Canseliet's ego-mortality as the final inner requirement.* Canseliet insists
that the Hermetic philosopher must genuinely release what he calls
"ego-mortality" — the attachment to individual identity — before approaching the
Stone. This is not a requirement of virtue or morality; it is a practical
requirement of the Work. The Stone, once approached, does not respond to the
practitioner's personal desires. It responds only to the universal principle
that the practitioner has become an instrument of.

The practitioner who has genuinely maintained the Oath across three years —
who has not sought recognition, has not exaggerated results, has worked in
the silence that the tradition demands — is the practitioner for whom ego-
mortality is not a teaching to be accomplished but a condition already partially
achieved.

=== Topics This Week

- Westcott's Cosmic level: what it feels like from inside the Work
- The Protyle and the Stone's projection as the natural consequence of correct Work
- Canseliet's ego-mortality: a practical requirement, not a moral ideal
- Assessing honestly where ego-mortality stands after three years

#inner-work[
  *Canseliet's Standard Applied*

  Write an honest paragraph in your inner work journal addressing Canseliet's
  standard directly: to what degree has personal identity been released in
  service of the Work across the three years? Where has ego-motivation (for
  recognition, for results, for the experience of having accomplished something)
  persisted?

  This is not a self-criticism exercise — it is a diagnostic. The practitioner
  who cannot identify any remaining ego-motivation has not been honest. The
  practitioner who identifies it precisely has the information needed to address
  it in the remaining months.
]

